trainingNotes.secondaryNote: Use the miCoach training diary to track your marathon training. Write about your training, how you felt, what you ate, etc. Identify what works and what doesn't.

trainingNotes.note: The steps should be very short bursts of speed. They help train the neuromuscular system to be faster. Go ahead and see how fast you can run in each red zone. Once you reach top speed, slow down again for a gentle recovery in the blue zone.
trainingNotes.secondaryNote: The time you spend in zones is a better way to measure training stress than distance. Two different runners can run different distances in a 50-minute green zone, but the training stress on their bodies will be the same. Forcing the two runners to run exactly 8 km could result in too much stress on one and not enough stress on the other.

trainingNotes.note: Take it easy today. Recovery is key to avoiding injury.
trainingNotes.secondaryNote: Heart rate helps you gauge your effort. As your fitness improves, you'll find that you can run faster for the same effort.

trainingNotes.note: Relax and enjoy the slow pace in the blue zones. This gentle effort helps improve the aerobic system while keeping the training stress at a minimum.
trainingNotes.secondaryNote: The time you spend in zones is a better way to measure training stress than distance. Two different runners can run different distances in a 40-minute green zone, but the training stress on their bodies will be the same. Forcing the two runners to run exactly 8 km could result in too much stress on one and not enough stress on the other.

trainingNotes.note: Speed is not important for this workout. Keep your effort comfortably within the zones.
trainingNotes.secondaryNote: This first week, focus on planning. Set aside time for these workouts. Decide when is the best time to do these workouts and stick to them. The goal for this first week is to start running regularly again.

trainingNotes.note: Run in the yellow zone at a steady pace. This should be somewhere between your 30K race pace and your half marathon pace.

trainingNotes.note: Relax and start with a slow run in the blue zone, then limit yourself to a comfortable run in the green zone. This workout should not exceed 22 km or 14 miles.
trainingNotes.secondaryNote: While heart rate zones will be tailored to your profile, pace zones are specifically related to your running goal. To complete a marathon in 2 hours and 50 minutes, adjust your zones from the "Settings" option so that the top pace of the red zone is 02:29:00 min./km (04:00:00 min./mile) and the top pace of the green zone is 03:56:00 min./km (06:20:00 min./mile).

trainingNotes.note: Think about today's pace. What feels natural, comfortable and sustainable to you?
trainingNotes.secondaryNote: Time spent in the green and blue zones is one of the pillars of this plan. If you increase your distance capacity in these zones, your body will make changes that will help you increase endurance.

trainingNotes.note: Run in the yellow zone at a steady pace. This should be somewhere between your 30K race pace and your half marathon pace.
trainingNotes.secondaryNote: Start at the bottom of the green zone and increase speed. Plan a smooth transition to enter the yellow zone.

trainingNotes.note: Take it easy today, save the motivation for tomorrow.
trainingNotes.secondaryNote: Knowing when to slow down or take a rest day is one of the secrets to marathon success.
